  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation moves a
shufflevector that uses a select (on LHS) to instead select between two shuffles
(FoldOpIntoSelect). This is poison-unsafe because select with a poison condition
yields poison for the entire result, while the original \"shuffle(select,
ConstRHS, Mask)\" can produce some defined lanes sourced from the RHS constant
even if the LHS (select) is poison. Thus, the transform increases poison, as
shown by Alive2.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe first transformation is in
visitShuffleVectorInst, where FoldOpIntoSelect is invoked for a shuffle whose RHS
is a constant and LHS is a select with integer condition:\n- Old: %shuf =
shufflevector %sel, ConstRHS, Mask\n- New: %shuf = select %cmp, shufflevector %y,
ConstRHS, Mask, ConstFoldedFalseArm\nAlive2 shows a counterexample with %cmp =
poison where the source has defined elements (1,3) s coming from RHS, but the
target is entirely poison because the select consumes poison condition.\n\n3.
Root Cause Analysis:\nFoldOpIntoSelect is being applied to a non-elementwise
operation (shufflevector with a mask that reads elements from both operands). The
comment in the code even warns \"We cannot do this fold for elementwise select
since ShuffleVector is not elementwise.\" Despite that, the fold is still
performed whenever RHS is constant and the LHS is a select with integer
condition. This is only safe if the shuffle mask references only the LHS (i.e.,
it is effectively elementwise on LHS). If the mask references RHS elements, the
operation can \"mask away\" poison coming from LHS/select and yield defined
values. Moving select after the shuffle reintroduces poison propagation from the
condition and is thus incorrect.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- File:
llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineVectorOps.cpp\n- Lines: 2903-2911\n-
Change: Guard the FoldOpIntoSelect for shuffle/select by ensuring it's only
applied when the mask extracts exclusively from LHS. This keeps the
transformation within the elementwise-safe case. Use the existing helper
isShuffleExtractingFromLHS(SVI, Mask).\n\nOriginal:\n  if (match(RHS,
m_Constant())) {\n    if (auto *SI = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(LHS)) {\n      // We
cannot do this fold for elementwise select since ShuffleVector is\n      // not
elementwise.\n      if (SI->getCondition()->getType()->isIntegerTy()) {\n
if (Instruction *I = FoldOpIntoSelect(SVI, SI))\n          return I;\n      }\n
}\n    ...\n  }\n\nReplacement:\n  if (match(RHS, m_Constant())) {\n    if (auto
*SI = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(LHS)) {\n      // We cannot do this fold for
elementwise select since ShuffleVector is\n      // not elementwise. Only safe if
the shuffle extracts exclusively from LHS.\n      if
(SI->getCondition()->getType()->isIntegerTy() &&\n
isShuffleExtractingFromLHS(SVI, Mask)) {\n        if (Instruction *I =
FoldOpIntoSelect(SVI, SI))\n          return I;\n      }\n    }\n    ...\n
}\n\nThis change ensures we only perform the fold when Mask references LHS-only
elements (< LHSWidth), which makes the shuffle behave elementwise with respect to
LHS and avoids the poison-hiding behavior from RHS constants.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nBy restricting the FoldOpIntoSelect transformation for
shuffle/select to cases where the mask extracts solely from the LHS, we prevent
incorrect poison propagation changes. The fix preserves correctness in scenarios
where RHS contributes defined elements under poison conditions, as in the
provided reproducer, and maintains the intended optimization where it is safe.",
